In this ode Horace thanks the Muses for the fa- vors they had bestowed on him, and especially for the friendship and protection of Augustus, which he ascribes entirely to their in- fiuence. He intimates that a love of poetry and elegant literature had inspired his patron with nobler sentiments and feelings than those of revenge and party strife.
